Ectosomal skeleton
: Ectosomal skeleton is membranous and contains the abundant large sigmas and smaller anisochelae. This ectosome is clearly seen on the filaments (
Figure 3 F
). The anisochelae are absent in the ectosome of the root like processes (
Figure 3 E
). In the stem of the sponge the mycalostyles echinate the endosomal columns of styles and the ectosome (
Figure 3 C
)

Endosomal skeleton
: In cross-section the stem has a radial skeleton, with a very small core. Around the nucleus seven arms radiate outwards (
Figure 3 A
). These arms are composed of flattened bundles of longitudinal mycalostyles, providing support to the sponge. In between these radiating arms and at right angles to them, there are also seven radiating wedges containing sigmas, anisochelae (
Figure 3 B
) and styles both longitudinally and radially orientated (
Figure 3 C
). From within these wedges the mycalostyles give rise to and support the filaments (lower 
Figure 3 D
).
